   "answer": 2,
   "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: C — It may have to reduce the different types of bread that it can offer.</h5><p><strong>Why C is correct:</strong> If production switching becomes too complex or costly, Warburton's may be forced to limit the number of different bread varieties it produces — reducing customer choice and potentially losing sales to competitors with wider ranges.</p><p><strong>Why the other options are wrong:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>A (Lower costs)</strong> — Lower costs is an ADVANTAGE of batch production, as specialist machinery can be used and production runs are efficient.</li><li><strong>B (Meets varied demand)</strong> — Meeting the needs of different customers is an ADVANTAGE — it is the main reason bakeries use batch production.</li><li><strong>D (Made to order / no storage needed)</strong> — Making bread to specific orders, reducing storage costs, is an ADVANTAGE of batch production.</li></ul></div>",
   "modelAnswer": ""
