   "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: D — profits totalling £45,000</h5><ul><li><strong>Working:</strong> ARR 10% of £150,000 = £15,000 average profit per year. Over 3 years: £15,000 × 3 = £45,000 total profit.</li><li><strong>Why A is wrong:</strong> £45,000 per year would be the total profit spread wrongly — that would imply an ARR of 30% per year, not 10%.</li><li><strong>Why B is wrong:</strong> £135,000 per year represents 90% ARR — far too high and comes from multiplying the investment by the years and the rate incorrectly.</li><li><strong>Why C is wrong:</strong> £15,000 is the average ANNUAL profit, not the total profit over 3 years.</li></ul><p><strong>Examiner's Comment:</strong> Only half of candidates identified D. Many chose A, suggesting they did not read carefully — £45,000 is the total over 3 years, not per year.</p></div>",
