  "key": {
   "answer": 1,
   "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: B — a financial ratio</h5><ul><li><strong>Why B is correct:</strong> GPM is a profitability ratio — a calculation that expresses one financial figure as a percentage of another (gross profit as a % of revenue).</li><li><strong>Why A is wrong:</strong> A computerised method of production is something like an automated assembly line — completely unrelated to financial performance.</li><li><strong>Why C is wrong:</strong> A pricing method (e.g. cost-plus pricing, penetration pricing) is how a business sets its selling price — not a measure of profitability.</li><li><strong>Why D is wrong:</strong> Variable costs are costs that change with output — not a financial ratio.</li></ul></div>",
   "modelAnswer": "B — a financial ratio. GPM = (Gross Profit ÷ Revenue) × 100. It is a profitability ratio that measures efficiency. Answer: B."
  }
