   "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: C — GLU plc spent more than £1.25 million on transport costs in 2018</h5><ul><li><strong>Working:</strong> 2018 total = £190,000 + £430,000 + £650,000 = £1,270,000 &gt; £1,250,000. ✓</li><li><strong>Why A is wrong:</strong> The data shows costs, not preference. Highest cost could mean they are forced to use air, not that they prefer it. No preference data is given.</li><li><strong>Why B is wrong:</strong> All three transport modes show rising costs year on year, not falling.</li><li><strong>Why D is wrong:</strong> The data shows the COST of transport, not the quantity of goods. Higher cost per rail doesn't mean more goods are transported by rail.</li></ul></div>",
   "modelAnswer": "2018 total transport cost = £190,000 + £430,000 + £650,000 = £1,270,000, which is more than £1.25m. Answer: C."
