   "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: B — Exceeds its break-even quantity (1 mark)</h5><p><strong>Why B is correct:</strong> At break-even, revenue exactly equals total costs. If a business sells more than the break-even quantity, revenue exceeds total costs, which is the definition of profit.</p><p><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>A:</strong> A positive bank balance shows liquidity (cash), not profitability. The money in the bank could have come from a loan.</li><li><strong>C:</strong> If costs are greater than revenues, the business is making a LOSS, not a profit.</li><li><strong>D:</strong> Paying off debts relates to solvency, not to whether revenue exceeds costs.</li></ul></div>",
