   "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: D — The company's revenue exceeded its costs (1 mark, AO2)</h5><p><strong>Why D is correct:</strong> Net profit = Revenue − Total Costs. If net profit is £16,000 (positive), then by definition revenue must have been greater than total costs.</p><p><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>A:</strong> The company might have spent or invested the profit money; profit and cash are different. The bank balance could be very low even with a good profit.</li><li><strong>B:</strong> A profitable business can still struggle to pay its bills if it has a cash flow problem (e.g. customers not paying on time).</li><li><strong>C:</strong> That would describe a net CASH OUTFLOW of £16,000 — meaning a cash deficit, not a profit. It is the complete opposite of what happened.</li></ul></div>",
   "modelAnswer": ""
